# Home Run Analysis Format — Gold Standard

When the user asks for a "home run analysis" or "HR analysis" for a specific batter, OR when generating Top 10 HR descriptions for the daily output, always produce the output in this **exact** structure, tone, and level of detail. This is the locked format. Do not abbreviate, summarize, or skip sections.

Pull all data from the project's cached Statcast, pitcher profiles, batter pitch profiles, BvP history, and model predictions.

## Canonical Example (match this exactly)

The following is the gold-standard output. Every HR description must match this depth, structure, and analytical voice.

---

**Brandon Lowe HR Analysis vs Miles Mikolas**

Model (tonight): Raw P(HR) 7.22% | Adj P(HR) 7.09% | Conf 0.982 (Medium)
3 PA vs starter: (1-(1-0.0722)^3 ≈) 20.1% raw | ~19.7% adjusted — about 1-in-5 either way.

Confidence factors: pitcher data 1.00 | BvP HR 1.05 | BvP hit 1.00 | staleness 0.85 | convergence HR 1.10 | convergence hit 1.00

**Career Power Profile**
157 career HR in 3,002 PA (5.23% HR/PA). League HR rate in this dataset is ~3.1% — Lowe is well above that (~1.7×). That's real power, not noise from a tiny sample.

Peak season: 2021 (39 HR).

Exit velocity on career HRs: mean 104.7 mph | max 114.3 mph — solidly hard HR contact vs league HR EV (~104 mph in this ballpark).

Launch angle on career HRs: mean 29.2 deg — normal fly-ball HR shape.

HR by pitch type (top): FF 60 (.226 BA in sample), CH 24 (.218), SL 19 (.155), FC 16 (.267), SI 14 (.249), CU 11 (.247). Four-seam is the engine — 4 of every 10 career HRs are off heaters. He still does damage on changeups and sinkers; slider is the weakest BA bucket but he still has 19 HR off SL. That's the math: Mikolas runs FF / SL / CU as his top three usage pitches — Lowe's 60 HR off FF and 11 off CU line up with what Mikolas actually throws.

One-sentence summary: Fastballs are the bread and butter — 60 of 157 career HRs came off FF, and he's shown he can elevate off Mikolas-type sinker stuff too.

**The Mikolas-Specific HR Case**
BvP: 1-for-5 (.200), 1 HR, 3 K in 5 PA. Sample is tiny, but it's not empty: one HR already on the board.

| Date (Statcast) | Pitch type | Velo | EV | LA |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| 2025-08-22 | SI | 93 mph | 110 mph | 31° |

That HR came on a sinker at 110 mph — violent contact. Mikolas leans sinker/four-seam/slider/curve; Lowe's BvP HR is on-brand with his SI/FF HR history.

Narrative: BvP K rate 60% (3 K in 5) is ugly — when he's not putting the ball in play, he's whiffing. When he does connect in this matchup, the ball has left before.

**Mikolas's HR Vulnerability**
Career: 155 HR allowed in 4,817 PA (3.22% HR/PA). That's right on the ~3.1% league average — career-wise he's not an extreme HR fountain.

HR allowed by pitch (top): FF 42, SI 37, SL 37, CU 22, CH 14.

Fastball: ~92.7 mph (profile), ~45% fastball-class usage — hittable velocity if location slips.

2026 (qualifying file): ERA 12.41, WHIP 2.35, BB/9 5.11, 12.3 IP, 5 HR allowed. That's catastrophic early form — you're not betting career Mikolas tonight; you're betting whatever this version is. The 5 HR in 12.3 IP is the flashing light for HR props.

vs LHB (Lowe bats left): 78 HR in 2,425 PA (3.22%) — same as vs RHB in this dataset; no platoon hide for Mikolas on HR rate.

K / BB: Career K% ~17.3%, BB% ~5.3% — he does not miss many bats relative to league; more balls in play means more HR variance when he's getting barreled (as 2026 suggests).

**Where Lowe Ranks Tonight**
#4 of 388 matchups by adj P(HR) — top ~1% of the slate.
#1 on PIT by adj P(HR) — best HR projection on the Pirates in this file.

**The Verdict on the HR Bet**
**For:** 5.23% career HR/PA crushes 3.1% league average — elite-tier HR frequency in the population. Raw and adj model are both ~7.2% / 7.1% per PA — more than double baseline. BvP already has 1 HR in 5 PA off this arm, and it was a 110 mph sinker bomb — lines up with Mikolas's SI/FF diet. 2026 Mikolas is leaking HR and ERA; low K% means Lowe gets looks. Confidence on HR is Medium with convergence_hr 1.10 (signals agreeing).

**Against:** 3 K in 5 BvP PA — when this matchup goes wrong, it goes strikeout wrong. Lowe's 27.2% career K rate is elevated; model P(K) ~32% tonight flags whiff risk. Mikolas's career HR rate is average — if you think 2026 is noise, you're fading the meltdown thesis. Staleness 0.85 still trims confidence (rolling data not "fresh April" in the same way as live 2026 box lines).

**Net:** ~7.1% per PA adjusted → ~19.7% over 3 PA — about 1-in-5. That's the slate's inner circle (#4 overall, #1 on PIT). This is both a power profile play (career HR rate + Mikolas arsenal overlap) and a current-form play on Mikolas 2026 — if you don't buy the 12 ERA stick, cut enthusiasm; if you do, Lowe is exactly the type of lefty power bat you'd short-list for HR.

